MiG-19s and 21s became available as early as 1966, when Indonesia (which operated both types) switched sides in the Cold War. Several more MiGs were captured intact by Israel during 1967. MiG-17s had fallen into western hands even earlier, notably from Morrocco, which had received some of these as a gift from the Soviet Union in the late 50s. MiG-23s and SU-20s were available from Egypt from 1977, the evidence for the former is especially strong (see YF-113 at FAS).  <br>
<br>
Lt. Viktor Belenko's MiG-25 was returned to the Soviets after his 1977 defection, but I have heard credible reports that a different MiG-25 was tested at Groom Lake and Edwards AFB shortly after that. The USAF's general evaluation of the MiG-25's capability changed considerably after the Belenko incident, much more so than one might expect from the hurried examination of his aircraft in Japan. <br>
My guess on the missing designations:<br>
F-112/MiG-19<br>
F-113/MiG-21<br>
F-114/MiG-23<br>
F-115/SU-22<br>
F-116/MiG-25 <br>
As for the &quot;F-19&quot;, I have  no idea, but Joe Baugher (a real expert) has some speculation at <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://home.att.net/~jbaugher4/f19.html">this page</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->.<br>
